on Goodwin Sands.

738
01:08:41,546 --> 01:08:45,676
- A life-saver.
- Aye. He did save many a life.

739
01:08:46,301 --> 01:08:50,306
But in the end...
he could not save his own.

740
01:08:50,430 --> 01:08:53,274
We never did find him, poor soul.

741
01:08:54,476 --> 01:08:59,027
My boy were eight year old
when he did lose his father.

742
01:08:59,147 --> 01:09:00,945
I was eight
when I lost my little sister.

743
01:09:01,066 --> 01:09:03,285
Oh? Oh, I am sorry.

744
01:09:07,823 --> 01:09:10,827
Well... 'tis the way of things.

745
01:09:16,331 --> 01:09:17,958
Ooh...

746
01:09:18,083 --> 01:09:21,428
You still making
your nice little pictures, Mr Mallard?

747
01:09:26,675 --> 01:09:27,676
There.

748
01:09:48,572 --> 01:09:50,290
Mr Billy.

749
01:09:54,744 --> 01:09:56,212
Welcome home.

750
01:09:57,747 --> 01:09:59,340
Dirty water.

751
01:10:09,801 --> 01:10:11,303
Pleasant trip?

752
01:10:14,848 --> 01:10:16,350
Your order came.

753
01:10:16,474 --> 01:10:20,195
- Did he send the cobalt blue?
- I put it in a jar.

754
01:10:20,312 --> 01:10:23,236
Chrome yellow, scarlet lake, lead white.

755
01:10:23,356 --> 01:10:26,360
- Canvases?
- He put 'em downstairs for me.

756
01:10:26,484 --> 01:10:29,328
Two six-by-fours,
three four-by-threes.

757
01:10:29,446 --> 01:10:32,120
- Megilp?
- Next week.

758
01:10:36,912 --> 01:10:38,914
Was it a pleasant trip?

759
01:11:11,404 --> 01:11:14,408
- Good morning, Mr Turner.
- Marlin, Sir Billy, Gussy.

760
01:11:14,532 --> 01:11:16,785
- Good day to you, Billy.
- Delighted you could join us.

761
01:11:16,910 --> 01:11:19,129
Damn fine spectacle this year, Billy.

762
01:11:19,245 --> 01:11:20,417
Aha!

763
01:11:21,957 --> 01:11:23,959
A very fine day to you, Mr Stothard!

764
01:11:24,084 --> 01:11:25,802
What? Oh!

765
01:11:25,919 --> 01:11:27,762
Mr Turner, sir!

766
01:11:34,386 --> 01:11:36,855
- Constable.
- Turner.

767
01:11:42,727 --> 01:11:45,321
- Jonesy, Carlo.
- William.

768
01:11:45,438 --> 01:11:46,781
The Hanging Committee.

769
01:11:46,898 --> 01:11:49,071
- You approve?
- 'Tis well hung.

770
01:11:49,192 --> 01:11:51,445
<i>- Grazie.
- Prego.</i>

771
01:11:53,321 --> 01:11:55,574
Would everything be
to your satisfaction, Mr Turner?

772
01:11:55,699 --> 01:11:57,622
It is indeed, Mr President.

773
01:11:57,742 --> 01:12:01,246
- 'Tis a splendid cornucopia,
- Cornucopia!

774
01:12:01,371 --> 01:12:04,671
- Good morning, Turner.
- Good morning to you, Mr Leslie.

775
01:12:04,791 --> 01:12:06,464
- Rabbie.
- Good morning, Mr Turner.

776
01:12:06,584 --> 01:12:08,177
My other piece,
where is it located?

777
01:12:08,294 --> 01:12:11,264
- We placed it in the anteroom.
- The anteroom.

778
01:12:11,381 --> 01:12:12,928
Oh.

779
01:12:14,342 --> 01:12:16,470
- Mr Carew!
- Turner!

780
01:12:18,138 --> 01:12:20,766
- Stanny.
- Hello, Mr Turner, sir.

781
01:12:21,850 --> 01:12:24,273
- Is it for His Majesty?
- Indeed.

782
01:12:24,394 --> 01:12:27,648
- I hope it meets his expectations.
- It will.

783
01:12:28,481 --> 01:12:30,700
- Grout.
- Mr Turner.

784
01:12:36,114 --> 01:12:40,745
- Ah! Sir John Soane!
- J. M. W. Turner, esquire!

785
01:12:40,869 --> 01:12:42,837
- As I live and breathe.
- My dear friend.

786
01:12:42,954 --> 01:12:44,547
Find yourself well, John?

787
01:12:44,664 --> 01:12:46,416
- Relishing the day.
- Capital.

788
01:12:46,541 --> 01:12:48,760
Only now I was admiring your seascape.

789
01:12:48,877 --> 01:12:50,379
There she is.

790
01:12:50,503 --> 01:12:53,507
- Mr Pickersgill.
- Good morning, William.

791
01:12:53,631 --> 01:12:55,008
Oh!

792
01:12:55,133 --> 01:12:57,056
He has the air of despondency upon him.

793
01:12:57,177 --> 01:12:59,475
- He is slighted.
- For why?

794
01:12:59,596 --> 01:13:02,065
Yet again in the anteroom,

795
01:13:02,223 --> 01:13:05,978
They hang us where they will, Pickers.
Take a guzzle of brown sherry.

796
01:13:06,061 --> 01:13:08,814
Damn fine storm you have there, Billy.

797
01:13:08,938 --> 01:13:11,532
Nimbus, Sir Billy, nimbus,

798
01:13:16,780 --> 01:13:19,203
Oh, beg your pardon, sir.

799
01:13:40,095 --> 01:13:43,850
- Carlo the Salamander.
<i>- Amico mio.</i>

800
01:13:43,973 --> 01:13:46,567
- Harmony and unity, William
- Chemise.

801
01:13:46,684 --> 01:13:48,686
- Chemise?
- Lower.

802
01:13:51,231 --> 01:13:53,029
<i>- Molto bene.</i>
- Jonesy!

803
01:13:53,108 --> 01:13:54,906
- I want you to see...
- What?

804
01:13:55,026 --> 01:13:56,619
- Remember?
- Remind me.

805
01:13:56,736 --> 01:13:58,613
- Pisa.
- Oh, Pisa!

806
01:13:58,738 --> 01:14:00,490
- Fine around there, Gussy.
- You think so?

807
01:14:00,615 --> 01:14:02,492
Oh, yeah.

808
01:14:04,953 --> 01:14:07,251
- Nelson?
- With two arms.

809
01:14:10,834 --> 01:14:12,507
- Mr Leslie,
- Turner.

810
01:14:12,627 --> 01:14:17,053
Little maid, gamboge gown,
left foot instep, touch of highlight.

811
01:14:18,049 --> 01:14:19,266
Thank you, Turner.

812
01:14:19,384 --> 01:14:22,103
Paintings always benefit his remarks.

813
01:14:22,220 --> 01:14:24,973
Carew!
This your man?

814
01:14:25,098 --> 01:14:26,645
'Tis he.

815
01:14:26,766 --> 01:14:29,394
Sports an elegant nostril,
does he not, Sir John?

816
01:14:29,519 --> 01:14:32,443
- Splendid nostrils.
- Thank you kindly.

817
01:14:32,564 --> 01:14:33,656
What did you say?

818
01:14:33,773 --> 01:14:36,276
Elegant pair of nostrils, Mr Stothard!

819
01:14:36,401 --> 01:14:38,403
Oh, yes, Yes, indeed.

820
01:15:25,450 --> 01:15:27,623
Why on earth would he go and do that?

821
01:15:27,744 --> 01:15:31,339
Oh, I believe Mr Turner knows
well enough what he's doing, Sir Martin.

822
01:15:31,456 --> 01:15:33,675
Do you think so?

823
01:15:33,791 --> 01:15:37,512
- He's ruined a masterpiece.
- I think not.

824
01:15:37,629 --> 01:15:40,132
That's too bad.
That's too bad.

825
01:15:41,382 --> 01:15:43,225
He's been here and fired a gun.

826
01:15:43,384 --> 01:15:45,386
Oh, no, no.

827
01:15:45,511 --> 01:15:48,731
John, you must not
upset yourself like this,

828
01:15:50,892 --> 01:15:52,940
The man's impossible.

829
01:15:53,061 --> 01:15:55,780
I mean, why would he go
and destroy a perfectly good painting?

830
01:15:55,897 --> 01:15:57,820
Sheer mockery.

831
01:15:59,484 --> 01:16:01,578
My sympathy is with Constable.

832
01:16:01,694 --> 01:16:05,198
He's got a damn fine picture here
and he's made a damn mockery of it.

833
01:16:05,323 --> 01:16:08,042
There's method
in the madness, gentlemen.

834
01:16:08,159 --> 01:16:11,413
- If that is method, it is pure madness.
- But, what is it? Is it...

835
01:16:11,537 --> 01:16:14,336
Oh, do stop that prattling laughter,
Mr Carew!

836
01:16:15,458 --> 01:16:18,382
I wager we've not seen
the end of this, gentlemen.

837
01:16:18,503 --> 01:16:20,050
He may surprise us yet.

838
01:16:22,173 --> 01:16:23,766
Haydon.

839
01:16:24,634 --> 01:16:25,681
Hey!

840
01:16:35,603 --> 01:16:39,733
Ah, Mr Turner.
We were just wondering if...

841
01:16:44,028 --> 01:16:45,746
I said he wasn't finished.

842
01:17:07,635 --> 01:17:10,138
- It's a buoy!
- Bravo!

843
01:17:10,263 --> 01:17:12,436
Bravo! Marvellous!

844
01:17:17,478 --> 01:17:19,572
Can you explain
your rendition?

845
01:17:19,689 --> 01:17:21,862
It needs no explanation, sir.

846
01:17:21,983 --> 01:17:24,987
'Tis our Redeemer's conveyance
into Jerusalem, plain as day.

847
01:17:25,111 --> 01:17:26,658
Blasphemy!

848
01:17:26,779 --> 01:17:28,406
You faring well, Mr Haydon?

849
01:17:28,531 --> 01:17:32,206
- This will be the finish of me!
- 50 pounds!

850
01:17:41,544 --> 01:17:43,922
Thank you, sir.
Thank you, sir, for your charity.

851
01:17:44,047 --> 01:17:46,300
- Haydon?
- You have been most kind.

852
01:17:46,424 --> 01:17:48,552
Most kind in your placement.
You have finished me.

853
01:17:48,676 --> 01:17:51,805
You might as well have taken my painting
and put it in the outhouse.

854
01:17:51,929 --> 01:17:54,182
Better yet, taken it out of this building
and thrown it in the Fleet.

855
01:17:54,307 --> 01:17:56,605
Haydon, I am hard... hard set

856
01:17:56,726 --> 01:17:58,694
- to understand your indignation.
- And as for you, my pupil...

857
01:17:58,811 --> 01:18:01,815
Your painting, sir, is hanging
next-door to that of Mr Turner.

858
01:18:01,939 --> 01:18:04,488
- It is in fine company.
- This is treachery!

859
01:18:04,609 --> 01:18:07,689
- And do not talk to me of Turners work.
- Please lower your voice, Mr Haydon.

860
01:18:07,695 --> 01:18:09,868
His pictures look as if they were
painted by somebody born without hands!

861
01:18:09,989 --> 01:18:11,616
Mr Haydon, what is your quarrel?

862
01:18:11,741 --> 01:18:14,301
What principles have you applied
other than those that I gave...?

863
01:18:14,369 --> 01:18:17,373
- Mr Haydon, please lower your voice.
- I will not, sir!

864
01:18:17,538 --> 01:18:19,779
- What is your quarrel here?
- I have no respect for you.

865
01:18:19,874 --> 01:18:22,878
I certainly do not acknowledge
your presidency.

866
01:18:23,002 --> 01:18:24,219
It should have been Wilkie.

867
01:18:24,337 --> 01:18:27,932
Mr Haydon, I will not have personal
attacks like this on the Academy ﬂoor.

868
01:18:28,049 --> 01:18:29,809
You will have
what I choose to give you, sir.

869
01:18:29,842 --> 01:18:31,282
This would be one
of the many reasons

870
01:18:31,386 --> 01:18:32,854
why you were never accepted here,
Mr Haydon.

871
01:18:32,970 --> 01:18:35,393
This man... this man has spent
a quarter of a century

872
01:18:35,556 --> 01:18:37,399
doing everything in his power
to malign me...

873
01:18:37,517 --> 01:18:39,877
- I have done nothing of the sort.
- ...and spoil my genius.

874
01:18:39,894 --> 01:18:41,737
- Refrain from this shouting, Mr Haydon.
- I will not!

875
01:18:41,854 --> 01:18:43,982
- I will have you forcibly removed.
- Yes, do it!

876
01:18:44,107 --> 01:18:46,405
Do it! Remove me
from your nest of portrait painters!

877
01:18:46,567 --> 01:18:47,489
Have a care!

878
01:18:47,610 --> 01:18:49,237
What, sir, is wrong
with being a portrait painter?

879
01:18:49,362 --> 01:18:50,864
What does it do to elevate the art?

880
01:18:50,988 --> 01:18:53,388
I received the accolade
from the King for painting portraits.

881
01:18:53,408 --> 01:18:55,877
- Oh, God! I bow to him!
- And damn good ones too, sir!

882
01:18:55,993 --> 01:18:59,918
Haydon, can I point out
that I, too, hang in the inferior chamber?

883
01:19:00,039 --> 01:19:02,167
I care not for your work, sir.
I care not a fig.

884
01:19:02,291 --> 01:19:06,091
At least my work does not represent
self-portrait as ass.

885
01:19:06,212 --> 01:19:09,056
Give me those...

886
01:19:11,884 --> 01:19:14,433
- Unhand me!
- Remove this man!

887
01:19:14,554 --> 01:19:17,023
You swines! You swines!

888
01:19:17,140 --> 01:19:19,643
Mr Haydon, sir,
with deep regret I must inform you

889
01:19:19,767 --> 01:19:22,111
that I am on my way to the porters,

890
01:19:22,228 --> 01:19:24,447
unless you feel free to leave
of your own volition.

891
01:19:24,564 --> 01:19:26,282
Shh, shh.

892
01:19:26,774 --> 01:19:28,276
Please, sir.

893
01:19:30,278 --> 01:19:32,872
Stretch me no longer on this rough world.

894
01:19:34,991 --> 01:19:36,834
I'm done with you.

895
01:21:15,508 --> 01:21:17,135
Oh!

896
01:21:44,245 --> 01:21:47,715
'Tis nice to have a bit of company
for a change.

897
01:21:47,832 --> 01:21:50,593
So you had a good walk, then?
Weren't too chippy up there by Reculver?

898
01:21:50,751 --> 01:21:54,176
Somewhat blowy and the wind
did kick up some white horses.

899
01:21:54,297 --> 01:21:56,015
Can do this time of year.

900
01:21:56,132 --> 01:21:58,180
In summertime, though,
'tis a lovely calm spot for a picnic

901
01:21:58,301 --> 01:21:59,678
up there by the Two Sisters,

902
01:21:59,802 --> 01:22:03,102
but in wintertime I have known
the whole of Marine Terrace down here

903
01:22:03,222 --> 01:22:06,476
without a pane of glass left
in the entire place.

904
01:22:06,601 --> 01:22:08,774
Oh, the glaziers do get rich.

905
01:22:09,812 --> 01:22:12,736
When Mr Booth and I moved in here,
we had the whole place polished up,

906
01:22:12,857 --> 01:22:15,155
spick and span,
ready for our first visitors

907
01:22:15,276 --> 01:22:17,950
and the wind did blow
and the sea come up.

908
01:22:18,070 --> 01:22:20,243
We had broken glass everywhere.
It were terrible.

909
01:22:20,364 --> 01:22:22,617
Mrs Booth.

910
01:22:22,783 --> 01:22:25,036
Would you be so kind
as to look out of the window?

911
01:22:27,121 --> 01:22:29,249
Where? What am I looking at?

912
01:22:29,373 --> 01:22:32,502
From the tip of your nose to the bridge
to the curve of your brow

913
01:22:33,586 --> 01:22:38,057
you put me in mind of a Greek sculpture
I'm familiar with, of Aphrodite,

914
01:22:38,841 --> 01:22:40,889
the goddess of love'

915
01:22:41,927 --> 01:22:44,646
Oh, now!

916
01:22:44,805 --> 01:22:46,853
No one's ever said that
about my nose before.

917
01:22:46,974 --> 01:22:48,100
This old snout!

918
01:22:53,314 --> 01:22:55,487
Truth to tell,
my eyes aren't so good these days

919
01:22:55,608 --> 01:22:59,784
so when I do look in the looking-glass
I be glad I cannot see so well.

920
01:22:59,904 --> 01:23:03,750
When I peruse myself in the looking-glass,
I see a gargoyle.

921
01:23:04,867 --> 01:23:06,665
Now, you be fishing for compliments,

922
01:23:06,786 --> 01:23:10,541
and my old ma used to say, them
what fish for compliments don't gel none.

923
01:23:10,665 --> 01:23:14,169
Besides, 'tis what's within a person
that do matter.

924
01:23:16,337 --> 01:23:18,760
I do not know you, Mr Mallard,

925
01:23:20,257 --> 01:23:25,184
and I'm sure there be things about you
that are beyond my understanding,

926
01:23:26,263 --> 01:23:28,937
but I believe you to be...

927
01:23:29,058 --> 01:23:33,154
a man of great... spirit
and fine feeling.

928
01:23:38,234 --> 01:23:39,702
Mrs Booth...

929
01:23:41,821 --> 01:23:44,825
...you are a woman
of profound beauty.

930
01:23:48,786 --> 01:23:50,288
Mr Mallard...

931
01:23:56,293 --> 01:23:58,466
I am lost for words.

932
01:24:00,464 --> 01:24:01,886
Hm.

933
01:24:24,029 --> 01:24:26,657
Good night, Mr Mallard, sir.

934
01:24:26,741 --> 01:24:28,743
I've cleaned your boots for'ee.

935
01:24:28,868 --> 01:24:30,711
They're by the door here.

936
01:24:33,998 --> 01:24:35,500
Mrs Booth.

937
01:24:37,543 --> 01:24:41,173
I thank you
for a most convivial evening.

938
01:24:41,297 --> 01:24:43,140
I do thank you too, sir.

939
01:26:19,103 --> 01:26:22,482
If I may be so bold as to say, mate,

940
01:26:23,941 --> 01:26:26,035
as I see it,

941
01:26:26,861 --> 01:26:29,239
you're a loose cannon
rolling round the deck.

942
01:27:15,784 --> 01:27:16,910
And out.

943
01:27:20,372 --> 01:27:22,500
Cover yourself up.

944
01:27:22,625 --> 01:27:23,922
Good man.

945
01:27:24,043 --> 01:27:27,638
Well, Mr Mallard
is suffering from bronchitis.

946
01:27:27,755 --> 01:27:29,302
Oh... there.

947
01:27:29,423 --> 01:27:31,721
For which we prescribe the three Bs:

948
01:27:31,842 --> 01:27:34,265
- bed, balsam and broth.
- Oh.

949
01:27:34,386 --> 01:27:38,266
To be administered in this case
by the fourth B: the admirable Mrs Booth.

950
01:27:38,390 --> 01:27:39,733
- Oh!
- Thank you.

951
01:27:39,850 --> 01:27:43,571
Now, Mrs Booth, if you would be so good
as to come up to the house after four,

952
01:27:43,687 --> 01:27:45,109
I shall have the balsam prepared.

953
01:27:45,230 --> 01:27:47,733
- Indeed I shall, sir.
- Good day, Mr Mallard.

954
01:27:47,858 --> 01:27:50,486
Rest the body, sir,
and the soul shall find solace.

955
01:27:50,611 --> 01:27:53,285
I do thank ye, Doctor.
Let me show ye out.

956
01:27:53,405 --> 01:27:55,578
- Good day to you, Mrs Booth.
- Good day to you, sir.

957
01:28:20,975 --> 01:28:22,022
Gentlemen.

958
01:28:22,184 --> 01:28:23,982
Ah, Mr Turner.

959
01:28:24,144 --> 01:28:28,274
My father and I are marvelling
at this glorious work.

960
01:28:28,399 --> 01:28:30,993
Er... might I be correct in remembering

961
01:28:31,110 --> 01:28:34,705
that we had the good fortune of viewing it
at the Academy last summer?

962
01:28:34,822 --> 01:28:35,948
Indeed.

963
01:28:36,031 --> 01:28:40,002
Well, I must say, it is no less impressive
on its second viewing.

964
01:28:40,160 --> 01:28:43,039
Perhaps even more so.
Is it not, Father?

965
01:28:43,205 --> 01:28:44,377
Indeed so.

966
01:28:44,498 --> 01:28:47,627
I recall it provoked
much heated and stimulating discussion

967
01:28:47,751 --> 01:28:49,719
long after our viewing.

968
01:28:49,837 --> 01:28:52,590
- It did not sell.
- Indeed not?

969
01:28:52,715 --> 01:28:54,683
No, Mr Ruskin.

970
01:28:54,800 --> 01:28:57,724
- I'm astonished.
- But it is a masterpiece.

971
01:28:57,845 --> 01:29:00,689
- Thackeray reviles it.
- How so?

972
01:29:00,806 --> 01:29:04,356
- Sublime or ridiculous, he says.
- Well, perhaps he should make up his mind.

973
01:29:04,476 --> 01:29:06,023
He has a sharp and cynical tongue.

974
01:29:06,145 --> 01:29:09,524
There is no place for cynicism
in the reviewing of art.

975
01:29:09,648 --> 01:29:11,241
Hm...

976
01:29:11,358 --> 01:29:13,986
- 'Tis of no consequence.
- Quite.

977
01:29:14,069 --> 01:29:16,037
It is purchasable.

978
01:29:17,239 --> 01:29:18,991
Enticing.

979
01:29:19,074 --> 01:29:20,951
Perhaps.

980
01:29:23,162 --> 01:29:28,168
Typhus epidemic amongst the cargo,
slaves die on board, no insurance.

981
01:29:28,292 --> 01:29:31,796
Sling 'em in the drink,
drowned dead, cash.

982
01:29:31,920 --> 01:29:34,764
I am struck by the column of bright white,

983
01:29:34,882 --> 01:29:38,056
placed precisely off centre here,

984
01:29:38,218 --> 01:29:41,973
applied over the darkened background,
impasto,

985
01:29:42,056 --> 01:29:47,233
contrasting with the scarlet and ochre hues
in the upper left corner,

986
01:29:47,352 --> 01:29:50,777
which in turn contrasts
with the presence of God,

987
01:29:50,898 --> 01:29:54,323
revealing to us that hope exists

988
01:29:54,443 --> 01:29:57,697
even in the most turbulent
and illimitable of deaths'

989
01:29:57,821 --> 01:29:59,243
Bluebottles.

990
01:30:00,199 --> 01:30:03,499
- Eh?
- Up in the muslin, Knock 'em out.

991
01:30:04,661 --> 01:30:06,914
Well, I didn't put 'em there.

992
01:30:10,334 --> 01:30:14,885
Would it not sit splendidly
above the fireplace in the library, Father?

993
01:30:15,005 --> 01:30:18,726
It would, but I fear
it may be beyond our purse, John.

994
01:30:18,842 --> 01:30:21,220
I'm sure some arrangement
can be come to, sir.

995
01:30:22,763 --> 01:30:24,436
Mind your heads.

996
01:30:26,058 --> 01:30:28,152
You're just...
you're just knocking 'em up and down.

997
01:30:28,310 --> 01:30:29,937
Scrape 'em out.

998
01:30:30,062 --> 01:30:32,440
Now you've...
Now you've knocked it over there.

999
01:31:10,018 --> 01:31:11,986
There. 'Tis a nice day for'ee.

1000
01:31:15,774 --> 01:31:17,902
<i>Au revoir, madame.</i>

1001
01:31:22,156 --> 01:31:23,783
T'other way.

1002
01:31:25,159 --> 01:31:27,207
- Morning, Mrs Stokes.
- Morning.

1003
01:31:57,733 --> 01:32:02,330
Dr Price, Mrs Booth has summoned you here
under false pretenses.

1004
01:32:02,446 --> 01:32:04,073
Shh! Let the doctor do his work.

1005
01:32:04,198 --> 01:32:05,495
Breathe in.

1006
01:32:07,075 --> 01:32:09,077
Breathe out

1007
01:32:09,203 --> 01:32:11,922
Have you been exerting yourself
unduly, Mr Mallard?

1008
01:32:12,039 --> 01:32:13,791
No more than is usual, sir.

1009
01:32:13,916 --> 01:32:15,714
Remind me again,
what is your profession?

1010
01:32:17,252 --> 01:32:20,051
- Master of Chancery,
- Breathe in.

1011
01:32:20,172 --> 01:32:22,345
Forgive me, sir,
but I beg to differ.

1012
01:32:22,466 --> 01:32:25,015
Breathe out

1013
01:32:25,135 --> 01:32:28,560
I suggest that you are Mr Turner,
the illustrious painter,

1014
01:32:28,680 --> 01:32:31,934
and I am greatly honoured
to make your acquaintance.

1015
01:32:32,809 --> 01:32:34,436
My apologies to you both,

1016
01:32:34,561 --> 01:32:37,405
but rest assured
that my discretion can be relied upon.

1017
01:32:38,649 --> 01:32:42,074
Now, allow me to examine your eyes.

1018
01:32:42,194 --> 01:32:44,993
The eyes of a master.

1019
01:32:45,113 --> 01:32:46,535
Open wide.

1020
01:32:47,282 --> 01:32:48,750
Mm-hm.

1021
01:32:49,618 --> 01:32:51,040
Look up.

1022
01:32:52,371 --> 01:32:53,793
Hmm.

1023
01:32:55,165 --> 01:32:58,510
Mr Turner, you are suffering
from a disorder of the heart.

1024
01:32:59,711 --> 01:33:02,089
There is no immediate
cause for concern, Mrs Booth.

1025
01:33:02,214 --> 01:33:04,216
- But he will have to be careful.
- Oh, dear.

1026
01:33:04,299 --> 01:33:09,681
Live moderately, sir, and you shall enjoy
a long and fruitful life.

1027
01:33:09,805 --> 01:33:13,981
Exert yourself unduly
and you will go to an early grave.

1028
01:33:14,101 --> 01:33:15,944
Oh, dear.

1029
01:33:17,437 --> 01:33:18,438
There, now.

1030
01:33:36,415 --> 01:33:38,167
Good day, sir.

1031
01:33:40,836 --> 01:33:43,009
Have you nothing to say to me?

1032
01:33:45,632 --> 01:33:47,885
I am most sorry for your loss.

1033
01:33:49,052 --> 01:33:51,054
Our loss, Father!

1034
01:33:51,179 --> 01:33:53,432
Your own dear daughter's funeral.

1035
01:33:53,557 --> 01:33:55,025
Indeed.

1036
01:33:58,312 --> 01:34:00,861
I did not find myself in the city.

1037
01:34:00,981 --> 01:34:05,532
As ever, sir,
painting your ridiculous shipwrecks.

1038
01:34:08,488 --> 01:34:10,490
Have you no feelings?

1039
01:34:12,659 --> 01:34:14,081
Speak!

1040
01:34:20,584 --> 01:34:22,336
Come, Evelina.

1041
01:34:22,502 --> 01:34:25,255
There is nothing here for us.

1042
01:35:14,388 --> 01:35:16,390
You're tired, my dear.

1043
01:35:19,851 --> 01:35:22,730
'Tis too much of a strain
for you these days,

1044
01:35:22,854 --> 01:35:27,200
trawling back and forth on that old steamer
every time you wants to see me.

1045
01:35:28,527 --> 01:35:32,248
And even when they've finished
building that new railway,

1046
01:35:32,364 --> 01:35:35,208
we none of us do know
what lies ahead.

1047
01:35:38,412 --> 01:35:41,086
I have bethought me of a plan

1048
01:35:41,206 --> 01:35:43,834
and here is what we must do.

1049
01:35:43,959 --> 01:35:45,632
If you will find
a little house for us,

1050
01:35:45,752 --> 01:35:50,178
somewhere by your beloved River Thames,
but not too far from London Town,

1051
01:35:50,841 --> 01:35:53,094
with good, solid, wooden ﬂoors,

1052
01:35:53,218 --> 01:35:55,641
nice bright light for you to work by...

1053
01:35:56,847 --> 01:35:59,020
...then I will buy the lease.

1054
01:36:02,686 --> 01:36:04,688
I can sell this house.

1055
01:36:06,857 --> 01:36:09,076
I think we would be happy.

1056
01:36:09,192 --> 01:36:10,785
The two of us.

1057
01:36:19,619 --> 01:36:21,087
There she is.

1058
01:36:21,204 --> 01:36:24,879
- The saucy Temeraire.
- Going to her death, I fear.

1059
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:26,422
She's served her time.

1060
01:36:26,501 --> 01:36:29,175
The auctioneer's hammer
has struck that final blow.

1061
01:36:29,296 --> 01:36:30,718
Indeed.

1062
01:36:30,839 --> 01:36:34,013
If not for her, the Victory might
never again have seen our shores.

1063
01:36:34,134 --> 01:36:36,102
Aye, nor the body of Lord Nelson.

1064
01:36:36,219 --> 01:36:39,143
The little saviour of Trafalgar.

1065
01:36:39,264 --> 01:36:43,485
They say 5,000 oaks
went into making that ship.

1066
01:36:43,643 --> 01:36:47,022
Now she's destined to be reduced
to 5,000 tables and chairs.

1067
01:36:47,147 --> 01:36:50,071
To be sat on by 5,000 fat arses.

1068
01:36:52,194 --> 01:36:53,662
Gentlemen, a toast.

1069
01:36:53,778 --> 01:36:57,908
Raise your pot of grog.
To the fine, fighting Temeraire!

1070
01:36:58,033 --> 01:37:00,456
- The Temeraire!
- The Temeraire!

1071
01:37:00,535 --> 01:37:02,082
Here's to her.

1072
01:37:04,289 --> 01:37:06,633
- A ghost of the past.
- No, Rabbie.

1073
01:37:07,417 --> 01:37:10,387
The past is the past.
We're observing the future.

1074
01:37:11,546 --> 01:37:15,176
Smoke, iron, steam.

1075
01:37:16,426 --> 01:37:18,426
She'd make a fine subject
for you to paint, Turner.

1076
01:37:18,512 --> 01:37:22,267
Oh, is that so, Stanny?
I shall cogitate upon it.

1077
01:37:23,225 --> 01:37:25,023
Thank you. Yeah, yeah.

1078
01:37:33,401 --> 01:37:36,371
It's that Mr Haydon.

1079
01:37:39,741 --> 01:37:42,745
He's brought a cold blast of air
in with him.

1080
01:37:50,544 --> 01:37:54,265
Mr Haydon, to what do I owe
the honour of your presence this morning?

1081
01:37:54,381 --> 01:37:58,011
I trust that this is not
an inconvenience to you, Turner.

1082
01:37:58,134 --> 01:38:01,729
Now, will you accept ten pounds?

1083
01:38:01,846 --> 01:38:04,565
- Ten pounds, sir?
- I wish to be free of the debt.

1084
01:38:04,683 --> 01:38:08,358
- It weighs heavily upon me.
- Sir, you owe me 50 pounds.

1085
01:38:08,478 --> 01:38:13,154
Manchester, Leeds, Newcastle,
I have been giving my lecture.

1086
01:38:13,275 --> 01:38:15,494
Edinburgh, fair city.

1087
01:38:15,569 --> 01:38:18,243
Only in London is my genius
not appreciated.

1088
01:38:19,531 --> 01:38:21,909
Consider this as a statement of intent.

1089
01:38:22,033 --> 01:38:24,912
- Mr Haydon, pray be seated.
- I had rather not.

1090
01:38:25,036 --> 01:38:27,164
I do not wish to prevail upon your time
more than is necessary.

1091
01:38:27,289 --> 01:38:29,462
And I prevail upon you, sir,
to take a seat.

1092
01:38:31,251 --> 01:38:33,720
- Where would you have me sit?
- Wherever you wish.

1093
01:38:36,590 --> 01:38:38,592
- Will this suffice?
- Indeed.

1094
01:38:38,758 --> 01:38:41,728
Mr Haydon, do you still find yourself
in a position of impecuniousness?

1095
01:38:41,845 --> 01:38:46,897
Impecunity? Turner, that has been
my constant state these 30 years.

1096
01:38:48,143 --> 01:38:50,566
You are most well-appointed here.

1097
01:38:51,313 --> 01:38:55,784
I do not recall the last time
we had as much coal in our scuttle as that.

1098
01:38:55,900 --> 01:38:58,494
I fear we shall be burning
our furniture this winter.

1099
01:38:58,612 --> 01:39:00,865
Does Mrs Haydon
find herself faring well?

1100
01:39:00,989 --> 01:39:04,539
She does not.
She has not recovered.

1101
01:39:04,618 --> 01:39:06,791
I fear that she may never do so.

1102
01:39:06,911 --> 01:39:08,754
What ails her, sir?

1103
01:39:09,664 --> 01:39:11,587
We have buried five children.

1104
01:39:13,251 --> 01:39:16,175
- Indeed?
- In Paddington old churchyard

1105
01:39:16,296 --> 01:39:19,175
they remove the soil,
extract the coffins,

1106
01:39:19,299 --> 01:39:20,596
dig the hole deeper,

1107
01:39:20,675 --> 01:39:24,475
then reinter the coffins
with another atop.

1108
01:39:24,596 --> 01:39:27,566
Five times
she has had to suffer that indignity.

1109
01:39:27,641 --> 01:39:30,520
- 'Tis pitiable.
- It is pitiable, Turner.

1110
01:39:31,269 --> 01:39:33,189
You have never had to endure
the loss of a child.

1111
01:39:34,981 --> 01:39:36,073
I have not, sir.

1112
01:39:36,191 --> 01:39:38,068
A dying child,

1113
01:39:38,193 --> 01:39:40,787
'tis a potent subject
for a painting, is it not?

1114
01:39:42,656 --> 01:39:45,034
And what is your present endeavour, Turner?

1115
01:39:45,158 --> 01:39:49,004
- Er... marine piece
- A marine piece?

1116
01:39:50,413 --> 01:39:52,882
Do not you tire of boats
and the fiery firmament?

1117
01:39:53,667 --> 01:39:55,089
I do not, sir.

1118
01:39:57,045 --> 01:39:59,514
Sometimes I consider
it might make a better course for me

1119
01:39:59,631 --> 01:40:01,633
were I to set light to the house

1120
01:40:02,717 --> 01:40:06,688
with my wife, my surviving children
and myself within it.

1121
01:40:06,846 --> 01:40:09,019
Then they would no longer
be saddled with me.

1122
01:40:09,349 --> 01:40:13,195
Your pain is your own, sir.
Do not inﬂict it upon your loved ones.

1123
01:40:15,647 --> 01:40:17,524
Will you take my ten pounds?

1124
01:40:19,693 --> 01:40:22,993
I will not, sir.
You are free of your debt.

1125
01:40:23,113 --> 01:40:25,662
- Free? How so?
- 'Tis expunged.

1126
01:40:25,740 --> 01:40:28,710
Er... no, sir. I do not come here
a seeker after charity or pity.

1127
01:40:28,868 --> 01:40:31,212
You have neither charity nor pity nor debt.

1128
01:40:31,329 --> 01:40:33,206
I do not wish it
in such a circumstance.

1129
01:40:33,331 --> 01:40:36,426
Mr Haydon, I am much preoccupied.

1130
01:40:36,543 --> 01:40:39,342
Me damsel, be so kind
as to escort the gentleman into the street.

1131
01:40:39,462 --> 01:40:41,135
Good day to you, sir.

1132
01:40:41,256 --> 01:40:43,725
This does not sit well with me, Turner.

1133
01:40:48,346 --> 01:40:49,472
Damn his eyes.

1134
01:40:49,597 --> 01:40:50,598
Oh...

1135
01:41:07,907 --> 01:41:11,036
- Turner and Jones.
- Mr Turner, Captain Jones.

1136
01:41:11,161 --> 01:41:13,289
- It's a pleasure to see you.
- Mr Ruskin!

1137
01:41:13,413 --> 01:41:14,460
Good evening to you.

1138
01:41:14,581 --> 01:41:15,981
I trust you had a pleasant journey?

1139
01:41:15,999 --> 01:41:17,717
Indeed. You find yourself well, sir?

1140
01:41:17,792 --> 01:41:20,796
I do indeed, thank you.
Pride of place, Mr Turner.

1141
01:41:20,962 --> 01:41:22,088
Ah, splendid.

1142
01:41:22,213 --> 01:41:24,432
As though the house
was built around it

1143
01:41:24,549 --> 01:41:27,052
- Please, come through'
- Jonesy.

1144
01:41:31,473 --> 01:41:33,066
Er, my good husband is of the opinion

1145
01:41:33,183 --> 01:41:36,483
that the gooseberry
prefers the colder climate,

1146
01:41:36,603 --> 01:41:40,073
whereas I consider
that all fruits benefit from the warmth.

1147
01:41:40,190 --> 01:41:44,536
My dear late mother always insisted
that both the gooseberry and the rhubarb

1148
01:41:44,652 --> 01:41:47,496
favour the colder climes
of our victorious isles.

1149
01:41:47,614 --> 01:41:52,165
I do not doubt that the gooseberry
for its preference may enjoy the warm,

1150
01:41:52,786 --> 01:41:57,462
however I am convinced that a cold start
promotes the more vigorous specimen

1151
01:41:57,582 --> 01:42:00,005
Are we not to take
as empirical evidence

1152
01:42:00,126 --> 01:42:04,302
our many expeditions
to the warmer climes of the Mediterranean

1153
01:42:04,422 --> 01:42:08,052
where we do not exactly encounter
an abundance of gooseberries?

1154
01:42:08,176 --> 01:42:10,804
- Ha! Indeed.
- Exactly so.

1155
01:42:10,929 --> 01:42:13,182
I did not myself savour
many gooseberries in Jerusalem.

1156
01:42:13,306 --> 01:42:15,934
Ah, the holy city, Mr Turner.

1157
01:42:16,059 --> 01:42:19,404
And yet we do enjoy
fine gooseberries in Scotland,

1158
01:42:19,521 --> 01:42:20,738
do we not, Mr Ruskin?

1159
01:42:20,814 --> 01:42:23,693
Aye, and no better a cold start
than a good Scottish sun.

1160
01:42:24,818 --> 01:42:25,990
Exactly that.

1161
01:42:26,110 --> 01:42:30,707
Surely, regardless of how cold the start
of the life of the gooseberry might be,

1162
01:42:30,824 --> 01:42:33,668
it is almost certainly destined
for a warm ending.

1163
01:42:33,785 --> 01:42:37,835
To which we have all borne witness
in Mrs Ruskin's excellent gooseberry pie.

1164
01:42:37,997 --> 01:42:40,967
I thank you, Captain Jones.

1165
01:42:41,084 --> 01:42:44,463
May I propose
as a topic for discussion

1166
01:42:44,587 --> 01:42:48,342
the question as to the depiction
of the seas and the oceans

1167
01:42:48,466 --> 01:42:49,968
in pictorial art?

1168
01:42:51,261 --> 01:42:54,265
Now, I appreciate
that I am honoured

1169
01:42:54,389 --> 01:42:58,860
to be in the presence of two
of our most distinguished marine painters,

1170
01:42:59,018 --> 01:43:02,363
Mr Turner and Mr Stanfield,

1171
01:43:02,480 --> 01:43:06,735
not to forget Captain Jones
and Mr Roberts, of course,

1172
01:43:06,860 --> 01:43:11,491
whose realisations are confined
to mere naked tetra firma,

1173
01:43:11,614 --> 01:43:13,241
exemplary though they are.

1174
01:43:15,368 --> 01:43:18,042
My point being that, alas,

1175
01:43:18,162 --> 01:43:22,884
I find myself harbouring
a perhaps rather controversial opinion

1176
01:43:23,042 --> 01:43:25,340
regarding the long deceased Claude

1177
01:43:25,461 --> 01:43:29,341
- Indeed?
- I am afraid so, Captain Jones.

1178
01:43:29,465 --> 01:43:31,342
I must confess

1179
01:43:31,467 --> 01:43:37,224
that I find his rendering of the sea
rather insipid, dull and uninspiring.

1180
01:43:37,348 --> 01:43:40,147
That is an extremely bold statement,
young Mr Ruskin.

1181
01:43:40,268 --> 01:43:41,895
Thank you very much.

1182
01:43:42,020 --> 01:43:43,897
Claude was a man of his time.

1183
01:43:44,022 --> 01:43:46,320
My point exactly, Mr Turner,

1184
01:43:46,441 --> 01:43:48,910
but that time is now long past.

1185
01:43:49,068 --> 01:43:52,789
When I experience
a modern masterpiece such as yours,

1186
01:43:52,906 --> 01:43:57,036
I am struck by the clarity
with which you have captured the moment.

1187
01:43:57,160 --> 01:43:59,458
Take, for example, your slave ship,

1188
01:43:59,579 --> 01:44:03,834
"Slavers Throwing Overboard
the Dead and Dying - Typhoon Coming On",

1189
01:44:03,917 --> 01:44:06,761
by which I have the good fortune
to be greeted every morning

1190
01:44:06,878 --> 01:44:09,222
on my way into my meagre breakfast.

1191
01:44:09,339 --> 01:44:13,845
The impact of the foaming brine incarnadine

1192
01:44:13,927 --> 01:44:17,898
consuming those unfortunate Negro slaves

1193
01:44:17,972 --> 01:44:21,852
never ceases to quicken
the beat of my heart.

1194
01:44:21,935 --> 01:44:25,735
Yet when I gaze
upon a work of Claude

1195
01:44:25,855 --> 01:44:28,074
I find myself enduring nothing more

1196
01:44:28,191 --> 01:44:31,365
than a mere collection
of precise brushstrokes

1197
01:44:31,486 --> 01:44:34,535
which instil in me
no sense of awe whatsoever,

1198
01:44:34,656 --> 01:44:36,078
let alone the sea.

1199
01:44:36,199 --> 01:44:37,701
Preposterous!

1200
01:44:38,159 --> 01:44:40,753
I do beg your pardon, Mrs Ruskin.

1201
01:44:42,789 --> 01:44:45,212
- Claude Lorrain was a genius.
- Quite so.

1202
01:44:45,333 --> 01:44:49,634
I sense an excess of modesty in Mr Turner
and there is no need for such humility.

1203
01:44:49,754 --> 01:44:51,597
Mr Ruskin, sir,

1204
01:44:51,714 --> 01:44:56,811
to conjecture upon the matter
of seascape painting is one thing

1205
01:44:56,928 --> 01:44:59,556
but to stand amongst the elements

1206
01:44:59,681 --> 01:45:04,778
and to experience
and to interpret what one sees

1207
01:45:04,894 --> 01:45:06,316
is something quite other.

1208
01:45:06,437 --> 01:45:08,189
- Hear, hear.
- Quite.

1209
01:45:08,314 --> 01:45:09,816
That is as it may be.

1210
01:45:09,941 --> 01:45:14,321
Claude painted from the land,
looking at the sea becalmed by the harbour.

1211
01:45:14,445 --> 01:45:17,039
- Oh, indeed.
- "Bless the Lord, oh my soul

1212
01:45:18,157 --> 01:45:20,831
"Who layeth the beams
of his chambers in the waters

1213
01:45:20,952 --> 01:45:23,455
"and walketh
upon the wings of the wind."

1214
01:45:23,579 --> 01:45:25,047
How apt, Mother.

1215
01:45:25,206 --> 01:45:26,503
Thank you, John.

1216
01:45:26,624 --> 01:45:27,750
Oh...

1217
01:45:27,875 --> 01:45:30,219
When my son was but a small boy,

1218
01:45:31,337 --> 01:45:33,510
he was overheard to remark that...

1219
01:45:33,631 --> 01:45:36,931
"waves of sea
are indeed lovely to watch

1220
01:45:37,010 --> 01:45:39,479
"but they are always coming or gone,

1221
01:45:39,595 --> 01:45:41,768
"never in any taken shape to be seen..."

1222
01:45:41,889 --> 01:45:43,562
- For a second,
- "...a second."

1223
01:45:45,601 --> 01:45:49,196
I find myself marvelling
at my own wealth of perception,

1224
01:45:49,313 --> 01:45:51,236
even at the early age of four.

1225
01:45:51,816 --> 01:45:53,033
Quite so.

1226
01:45:53,151 --> 01:45:57,497
Mr Ruskin, can I pose you
a somewhat conundrous question?

1227
01:45:57,613 --> 01:45:59,456
Ah, please do, Mr Turner.

1228
01:46:01,868 --> 01:46:04,997
To which do you find yourself
the more partial,

1229
01:46:05,079 --> 01:46:09,676
a... steak and kidney pie
or a veal and ham pie?

1230
01:46:13,713 --> 01:46:16,011
I must confess, Mr Turner,

1231
01:46:16,090 --> 01:46:19,185
that I find myself quite unable
to answer your question

1232
01:46:19,302 --> 01:46:21,976
with the precision
that I would wish.

1233
01:47:35,545 --> 01:47:37,047
Your Majesty.

1234
01:47:59,026 --> 01:48:00,778
Terribly ﬂat.

1235
01:48:01,988 --> 01:48:04,582
- Dull.
- It's rather dark, isn't it?

1236
01:48:05,992 --> 01:48:08,086
- Sir Martin.
- Sir?

1237
01:48:08,161 --> 01:48:11,631
- Who is the artist?
- I believe, sir, it's...

1238
01:48:17,336 --> 01:48:19,213
Mr John Ferneley, sir.

1239
01:48:19,380 --> 01:48:21,599
- Oh, Mr Ferneley.
- Hm.

1240
01:48:30,850 --> 01:48:32,318
Ah...

1241
01:48:43,863 --> 01:48:45,615
Turner.

1242
01:48:45,740 --> 01:48:48,209
He is clearly losing his eyesight.

1243
01:48:51,537 --> 01:48:53,960
And this one is vile.

1244
01:48:57,793 --> 01:48:58,885
Unbelievable.

1245
01:48:59,003 --> 01:49:01,131
- What it that?
- I don't know.

1246
01:49:01,214 --> 01:49:03,683
A dirty, yellow mess.

1247
01:49:14,769 --> 01:49:17,522
It is a truly frightful piece.

1248
01:49:17,647 --> 01:49:20,617
It is indicative of mental disease.

1249
01:49:20,733 --> 01:49:22,952
It is wretched and abortive.

1250
01:49:27,073 --> 01:49:28,575
Sad.

1251
01:49:29,075 --> 01:49:33,421
Mr Turner seems
to have taken leave of form altogether.

1252
01:49:33,537 --> 01:49:36,131
He has on former occasion
chosen to paint

1253
01:49:36,249 --> 01:49:40,755
with cream or chocolate,
yolk of egg or currant jelly.

1254
01:49:40,878 --> 01:49:45,133
But here he uses
his whole array of kitchen stuff.

1255
01:49:45,258 --> 01:49:49,809
- Eggs and spinach.
- No, soap suds and whitewash.

1256
01:49:51,055 --> 01:49:54,434
Jam tarts! Jam tans!
Fresh jam tarts!

1257
01:50:03,067 --> 01:50:04,284
Oh!

1258
01:50:04,402 --> 01:50:06,154
Where is that wretched baker's boy?

1259
01:50:06,279 --> 01:50:08,122
His fate, I fear, he won't enjoy.

1260
01:50:08,239 --> 01:50:10,333
He will indeed the lad destroy!

1261
01:50:10,491 --> 01:50:11,413
Aha!

1262
01:50:11,534 --> 01:50:13,286
I have an inspiration.

1263
01:50:13,411 --> 01:50:16,210
- What's that?
- We're filled with fascination.

1264
01:50:16,289 --> 01:50:18,758
- What is he doing?
- And why is he doing it?

1265
01:50:18,874 --> 01:50:21,798
Whatever he's brewing,
we'll soon be viewing it.

1266
01:50:21,919 --> 01:50:26,595
A masterpiece I here present
which Mr Turner has just sent.

1267
01:50:28,342 --> 01:50:33,189
While mostly blessed
with good intent, we have our doubts.

1268
01:50:33,306 --> 01:50:35,479
But who's this gent?

1269
01:50:35,599 --> 01:50:38,603
Ye common throng and hoi polloi,

1270
01:50:38,728 --> 01:50:41,322
I am a rich and cultured boy.

1271
01:50:41,439 --> 01:50:44,568
My wealth derives
from tricking knaves

1272
01:50:44,692 --> 01:50:47,161
and selling coffee, tea and slaves.

1273
01:50:47,278 --> 01:50:50,157
My house is full of things of beauty,

1274
01:50:50,281 --> 01:50:53,125
paintings, sculpture and other booty.

1275
01:50:53,242 --> 01:50:56,496
I like to drink and gourmandise...

1276
01:50:56,620 --> 01:50:58,338
But what is this that greets my eyes?

1277
01:50:58,497 --> 01:51:00,170
It is the latest thing in art.

1278
01:51:00,291 --> 01:51:02,589
It looks like bits of old jam tart.

1279
01:51:02,710 --> 01:51:07,682
'Tis Mr Turner's latest piece,
which placed above your mantelpiece...

1280
01:51:07,798 --> 01:51:10,551
Oh, cease your costermonger sounds!

1281
01:51:10,676 --> 01:51:12,178
I'll buy it.

1282
01:51:13,346 --> 01:51:17,567
- Here's 1,000 pounds.
- Oh, I thank you in my humble way.

1283
01:51:17,683 --> 01:51:21,563
- Don't grovel, send it round today.
- I'll do so, sir, without delay.

1284
01:51:21,687 --> 01:51:24,987
Rejoice! Hurrah!
Hip, hip, hooray!

1285
01:51:25,775 --> 01:51:27,823
Though ignorant of an and taste,

1286
01:51:27,902 --> 01:51:29,996
I'm filled with boundless glee,

1287
01:51:30,112 --> 01:51:33,958
for what's good enough for Turner...
is good enough for me!

1288
01:52:15,574 --> 01:52:18,953
Mr Ruskin, I fail to see
wherein lies the charity

1289
01:52:19,078 --> 01:52:21,957
in misleading people
as to the amount of talents they possess.

1290
01:52:22,081 --> 01:52:23,754
Talent is something
that lies dormant

1291
01:52:23,874 --> 01:52:26,172
and needs to be drawn out
in the right circumstances.

1292
01:52:26,293 --> 01:52:28,842
If one has the opportunity
to have it drawn out.

1293
01:52:28,963 --> 01:52:32,058
My wife, Effie,

1294
01:52:32,174 --> 01:52:36,054
I am still waiting for her talents
to arise and be drawn out.

1295
01:52:36,178 --> 01:52:39,432
I think talents can be crushed
as much as they may be drawn out.

1296
01:52:39,557 --> 01:52:40,604
Precisely.

1297
01:52:40,724 --> 01:52:41,941
Perhaps it is the duty
of the husband...

1298
01:52:42,059 --> 01:52:46,439
Plutarch said,
"Painting is silent poetry."

1299
01:53:01,954 --> 01:53:04,833
Are you interested in poetry, sir?

1300
01:53:04,957 --> 01:53:07,676
Sublime.

1301
01:53:14,175 --> 01:53:15,472
Loneliness...

1302
01:53:17,970 --> 01:53:19,972
...solitude...

1303
01:53:20,973 --> 01:53:23,476
...'tis not the same.

1304
01:53:25,019 --> 01:53:28,023
Indeed not, Mr Turner.

1305
01:53:29,148 --> 01:53:30,866
It will come.

1306
01:53:32,359 --> 01:53:36,956
Mrs Ruskin... it will come.

1307
01:53:39,283 --> 01:53:40,626
Love.

1308
01:53:52,505 --> 01:53:54,428
Oh...

1309
01:53:55,883 --> 01:53:57,476
What is the hour?

1310
01:53:57,551 --> 01:53:59,895
- Five-and-twenty to seven.
- Oh.

1311
01:54:00,012 --> 01:54:01,514
Oh, God!

1312
01:54:02,264 --> 01:54:03,982
Oh...

1313
01:54:12,149 --> 01:54:14,993
The sun's up in all its glory.

1314
01:54:15,653 --> 01:54:17,496
I must get on.

1315
01:54:37,925 --> 01:54:40,769
- Don't you want your breakfast?
- No, thank you kindly.

1316
01:54:46,183 --> 01:54:48,311
Are you faring well?

1317
01:54:48,435 --> 01:54:50,403
Yes, thank you'

1318
01:54:51,730 --> 01:54:54,449
- And yourself?
- Yes, yes.

1319
01:54:57,236 --> 01:54:59,580
Will I be seeing you tonight?

1320
01:54:59,697 --> 01:55:01,916
- Unlikely.
- Tomorrow?

1321
01:55:03,617 --> 01:55:05,711
- No.
- Oh.

1322
01:55:09,582 --> 01:55:12,756
I might as well stop
changing the bed sheets in here.

1323
01:55:42,573 --> 01:55:44,075
Mr Booth!

1324
01:56:08,182 --> 01:56:09,650
Good day to you.

1325
01:56:20,986 --> 01:56:23,785
- 'Tis warmer now.
- Sultry day.

1326
01:56:27,660 --> 01:56:30,334
- Ooh, what d'you have there?
- Bit of drift bark.

1327
01:56:30,454 --> 01:56:32,206
Ooh!

1328
01:56:32,331 --> 01:56:34,333
Has the look of a fallen angel.

1329
01:56:35,501 --> 01:56:38,050
- Pretty colours.
- Mm.

1330
01:56:41,632 --> 01:56:43,350
Oh! Sticky.

1331
01:56:46,261 --> 01:56:47,934
Horrid parched,

1332
01:57:22,297 --> 01:57:25,301
- Good morning, sir.
- A very good day to you, sir.

1333
01:57:25,426 --> 01:57:27,349
- Nice day, sir.
- Mm-hm.

1334
01:57:34,643 --> 01:57:36,441
Ah! Good morning, sir.

1335
01:57:36,562 --> 01:57:38,360
Greetings and welcome.

1336
01:57:38,480 --> 01:57:40,107
A hearty good morning to you, sir.

1337
01:57:40,232 --> 01:57:43,111
- Now, you would be Mr...
- Mr Booth.

1338
01:57:43,235 --> 01:57:46,079
Ah, Booth, yes. Mr Booth.

1339
01:57:46,196 --> 01:57:48,915
- At the appointed hour, I believe.
- Indeed, sir.

1340
01:57:49,032 --> 01:57:50,659
Mayall, John Mayall.

1341
01:57:50,743 --> 01:57:52,586
I had made that assumption, sir.

1342
01:57:52,703 --> 01:57:54,797
At your service, Mr Booth,

1343
01:57:54,955 --> 01:57:58,585
Now, if you would be so kind
as to make yourself comfortable...

1344
01:57:58,709 --> 01:58:01,178
- This is the contraption?
- Indeed, sir.

1345
01:58:01,295 --> 01:58:03,514
That is what we call the camera.

1346
01:58:04,423 --> 01:58:06,767
- The cam-ra?
- Yes, sir.

1347
01:58:06,884 --> 01:58:08,261
Not the cam-er-ah?

1348
01:58:08,385 --> 01:58:11,104
Er... no, sir.
The camera.

1349
01:58:11,221 --> 01:58:13,144
- The camera?
- Yes, sir.

1350
01:58:13,265 --> 01:58:15,359
As in camera obscura?

1351
01:58:15,476 --> 01:58:18,400
Ah, precisely, sir.
The camera.

1352
01:58:18,520 --> 01:58:21,273
Now, if I may ask you
to take a seat, please, here.

1353
01:58:21,398 --> 01:58:23,571
- Name of manufacturer?
- Er...

1354
01:58:23,692 --> 01:58:25,786
It comes to us
from the United States, sir.

1355
01:58:25,944 --> 01:58:27,821
The name eludes you?

1356
01:58:27,988 --> 01:58:29,615
Oh, no, sir.

1357
01:58:30,491 --> 01:58:33,586
My name eludes me
from time to time.

1358
01:58:33,702 --> 01:58:35,500
Indeed, sir?

1359
01:58:36,663 --> 01:58:37,789
Now...

1360
01:58:37,915 --> 01:58:39,337
Hm...

1361
01:58:46,089 --> 01:58:50,469
I denote from your brogue
that you hail from the Americas.

1362
01:58:50,594 --> 01:58:52,813
From the fine city of Philadelphia, sir.

1363
01:58:52,930 --> 01:58:55,649
Philadelphia?
'Tis on the eastern coast, is it not?

1364
01:58:55,766 --> 01:58:57,018
That is correct, sir.

1365
01:58:57,142 --> 01:58:58,359
Ow!

1366
01:58:58,477 --> 01:59:01,947
You shall have to forgive
the whip-crack of my knees.

1367
01:59:02,064 --> 01:59:06,240
- Hat on or hat off?
- Er... may I ask your profession, sir?

1368
01:59:06,985 --> 01:59:08,703
Master of Chancery.

1369
01:59:08,821 --> 01:59:11,415
- A man of the law.
- Indeed.

1370
01:59:11,532 --> 01:59:15,002
Then I should recommend the hat on, sir.

1371
01:59:15,118 --> 01:59:18,497
Now, if I might deploy this device...

1372
01:59:18,622 --> 01:59:20,420
Hey!

1373
01:59:21,250 --> 01:59:22,843
What is this heinous implement?

1374
01:59:23,001 --> 01:59:25,254
Merely a gentle holding brace, sir.

1375
01:59:25,379 --> 01:59:27,256
Puts me in mind of a surgical instrument.

1376
01:59:27,798 --> 01:59:30,142
- Dues it hurt?
- Not in the slightest, I assure you.

1377
01:59:30,259 --> 01:59:32,478
So, if I may...

1378
01:59:35,806 --> 01:59:38,184
Not too uncomfortable for you, Mr Booth?

1379
01:59:39,768 --> 01:59:40,815
Thank you, sir.

1380
01:59:40,894 --> 01:59:43,613
What is the significance
of the looking-glass?

1381
01:59:43,730 --> 01:59:47,780
It is to illuminate your good self, sir.

1382
01:59:50,487 --> 01:59:52,114
As the sun upon a lake.

1383
01:59:52,239 --> 01:59:55,869
Oh! Most droll, Mr Booth.

1384
01:59:55,993 --> 01:59:57,210
Most droll.

1385
02:00:00,122 --> 02:00:03,672
What is concealed
behind the small brass cap?

1386
02:00:03,792 --> 02:00:08,047
- An optic?
- Yes, sir, a glass lens.

1387
02:00:08,171 --> 02:00:09,514
As a telescope?

1388
02:00:10,382 --> 02:00:12,851
Not unlike a telescope, sir.

1389
02:00:12,926 --> 02:00:14,519
Thank you, Cornelius,

1390
02:00:14,636 --> 02:00:17,480
- It is prismatic?
- I fear not, sir.

1391
02:00:17,598 --> 02:00:20,226
- It is an achromatic lens.
- Achromatic.

1392
02:00:20,350 --> 02:00:22,773
Now, let me peruse you.

1393
02:00:24,521 --> 02:00:27,900
Why are you shrouded
in the manner of a condemned monk?

1394
02:00:28,066 --> 02:00:30,910
I am simply shutting out the light,
Mr Booth.

1395
02:00:32,487 --> 02:00:34,831
Ah, splendid, sir.

1396
02:00:34,907 --> 02:00:37,535
The image you create
is not of colour.

1397
02:00:37,659 --> 02:00:38,911
For why?

1398
02:00:39,077 --> 02:00:42,832
Er... I am afraid that is a question
we have yet to answer, sir.

1399
02:00:42,915 --> 02:00:44,883
It is a mystery.

1400
02:00:44,958 --> 02:00:46,210
Thank you, Cornelius,

1401
02:00:46,335 --> 02:00:48,838
And long may it remain so.

1402
02:00:48,921 --> 02:00:53,552
Now, if I may ask you
to focus your gaze here, on the ﬂowers,

1403
02:00:53,675 --> 02:00:56,269
and we are almost ready.

1404
02:00:56,386 --> 02:00:57,979
Thank you, Cornelius,

1405
02:01:02,851 --> 02:01:03,852
Now...

1406
02:01:03,936 --> 02:01:08,908
I will require your absolute stillness
for the next ten seconds.

1407
02:01:12,903 --> 02:01:15,281
And... we begin.

1408
02:01:35,592 --> 02:01:37,686
And there we have it.

1409
02:01:37,803 --> 02:01:41,273
- 'Tis done?
- It is finished, sir.

1410
02:01:42,349 --> 02:01:44,943
I fear that I, too, am finished.

1411
02:01:45,018 --> 02:01:46,861
Oh, come, come, sir.

1412
02:01:50,357 --> 02:01:52,030
This be one of them there photographs.

1413
02:01:53,235 --> 02:01:55,488
The Queen had one of these taken
with Prince Albert.

1414
02:01:55,612 --> 02:01:57,614
- Did she so?
- She did.

1415
02:01:57,739 --> 02:01:59,616
- Oh!
- Hm.

1416
02:01:59,741 --> 02:02:02,290
Oh, you do look most handsome.

1417
02:02:02,411 --> 02:02:04,459
- 'Tis known as a daguerreotype.
- Oh.

1418
02:02:05,580 --> 02:02:07,002
Whatever next?

1419
02:02:08,000 --> 02:02:10,594
- Where'd you have this done, then?
- Up in town on the Strand.

1420
02:02:10,711 --> 02:02:12,213
Fellow with a box.

1421
02:02:18,135 --> 02:02:19,853
- We're going there.
- Where?

1422
02:02:19,970 --> 02:02:22,018
- Have our likeness taken.
- When?

1423
02:02:22,180 --> 02:02:24,182
- Thursday.
- Oh.

1424
02:02:24,307 --> 02:02:26,526
I've arranged an appointment.

1425
02:02:26,643 --> 02:02:29,021
- Well, you'll have to cancel it.
- 'Tis painless.

1426
02:02:29,146 --> 02:02:30,944
Oh, I care not.

1427
02:02:31,023 --> 02:02:33,151
You don't want my old face
in one of these.

1428
02:02:33,275 --> 02:02:35,778
I do, the two of us together.

1429
02:02:36,695 --> 02:02:38,242
Forever.

1430
02:02:41,366 --> 02:02:43,334
I do thank you for this.

1431
02:02:44,202 --> 02:02:46,045
But I ain't going.

1432
02:02:50,667 --> 02:02:52,419
'Tis the camera.

1433
02:02:54,004 --> 02:02:56,678
Mr Mayall, may I beg your indulgence
with a question?

1434
02:02:56,798 --> 02:02:58,050
Why, certainly, sir.

1435
02:02:58,175 --> 02:03:00,052
Do you take landscapes
with your contraption?

1436
02:03:00,177 --> 02:03:03,101
- I do, sir, from time to time.
- Such as what?

1437
02:03:03,263 --> 02:03:06,312
Why, I have recorded
the great falls of Niagara, sir.

1438
02:03:07,350 --> 02:03:09,978
- The Niagara Falls?
- Indeed, sir.

1439
02:03:10,062 --> 02:03:12,190
The greatest wonder in nature.

1440
02:03:12,314 --> 02:03:15,989
It was there that I was once able
to capture a rainbow.

1441
02:03:17,652 --> 02:03:19,575
I'm green-eyed with envy.

1442
02:03:20,697 --> 02:03:22,540
The Niagara Falls...

1443
02:03:23,241 --> 02:03:26,996
Wis a natural phenomenon
that I have long desired to witness.

1444
02:03:27,079 --> 02:03:28,706
Is that so, sir?

1445
02:03:28,830 --> 02:03:32,505
Now, madam, sir,
if I may ask you to fix your gaze here

1446
02:03:32,626 --> 02:03:34,594
upon these beautiful ﬂowers.

1447
02:03:34,711 --> 02:03:36,304
Thank you, Cornelius.

1448
02:03:36,421 --> 02:03:37,843
Niagara Falls.

1449
02:03:39,758 --> 02:03:42,602
Soon painters will go about the world

1450
02:03:42,719 --> 02:03:45,563
with a box, like a tinker,

1451
02:03:45,680 --> 02:03:48,684
instead of a portfolio under their arms,

1452
02:03:48,809 --> 02:03:51,938
Well, I'm sure they will, sir.
I'm sure they will.

1453
02:03:53,313 --> 02:03:57,363
Now, if you are comfortable,
madam, sir,

1454
02:03:57,484 --> 02:03:59,737
we may proceed,

1455
02:04:32,561 --> 02:04:34,484
- Thank you, miss.
- Thank you, sir.

1456
02:04:41,319 --> 02:04:44,448
- Your good health, sir.
- And yours, Mr Gillott.

1457
02:04:48,702 --> 02:04:50,079
- Turner.
- Sir.

1458
02:04:50,162 --> 02:04:52,506
- I have a proposition to make.
- Oh?

1459
02:04:52,622 --> 02:04:54,920
- I like your pictures.
- Well, thank you, sir.

1460
02:04:55,041 --> 02:04:56,509
My wife is especially partial

1461
02:04:56,626 --> 02:04:59,300
to your companion pieces
that grace our drawing room.

1462
02:04:59,421 --> 02:05:02,220
Please convey my felicitations
to your dear lady.

1463
02:05:02,382 --> 02:05:04,180
I will, thank you.

1464
02:05:06,303 --> 02:05:09,182
And now I wish to show you
one of my pictures.

1465
02:05:09,347 --> 02:05:11,850
Oh, indeed, sir?
I am much intrigued.

1466
02:05:16,521 --> 02:05:18,398
Five-pound note,
